# K6Testing

### Description

An introduction to writing performance tests for Web Api using K6

### Dependencies:

- K6: winget install k6 --source winget
    - K6 can be installed in other ways, see [K6 installation](https://grafana.com/docs/k6/latest/set-up/install-k6/) 

### Run performance tests

- Run the project K6Testing.AppHost. Note the project is setup with .NET Aspire.
- Navigate to K6Testing -> Scripts folder and run `k6 run {script file}`.
- To enable Dashboard on http://localhost:5665/ during running of tests, set the environment variable to true `$env:K6_WEB_DASHBOARD = "true"`. Note that the dashboard is only available while the tests are executing. 
Once the tests have completed, the Dashboard is no longer available.

### Enabling ES6 features and NodeJS node modules resolution

- Navigate to K6Testing -> Scripts -> enable-es6-features-webpack folder and run the tests using `k6 run {script file}`. You will see that the test fails because `Lodash` cannot be resolved.
- Run `npm run bundle` to transpile the project into commonjs (Vanilla javascript - ES5) using webpack.
- The transpiled files will be available in the `dist` folder. You can run the tests using `k6 run dist/{script file}`. The tests should now run successfully with the `Lodash` dependency resolved.

##### Setup

- To enable ES6 features and NodeJS node modules resolution, you need to initialize a NodeJS Project by running `npm init -y`.
and install `npm install` the necessary node modules (see package.json) to transpile the project into commonjs (Vanilla javascript - ES5) using webpack.
- Once the dependencies has been resolve, run `npm run bundle` to transpile the project into commonjs (Vanilla javascript - ES5) using webpack.

### Streaming K6 metadata to DataDog

- Run the following command to start a DataDog Agent. Replace the ApiKey before running the command:
```
docker run --rm -d --name datadog -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock:ro -v /proc/:/host/proc/:ro -v /sys/fs/cgroup/:/host/sys/fs/cgroup:ro -e DD_SITE="datadoghq.eu" -e DD_API_KEY={ApiKey} -e DD_DOGSTATSD_NON_LOCAL_TRAFFIC=1 -p 8125:8125/udp datadog/agent:latest 
```
- We need to create a binary that includes https://github.com/LeonAdato/xk6-output-statsd.
  - To build a k6 binary with this extension, first ensure you have the prerequisites:
    - [Go toolchain](https://go101.org/article/go-toolchain.html) - Download msi and install
    - [Git](https://git-scm.com/) - Download and install Git
    - [xk6](https://github.com/grafana/xk6) - Run `go install go.k6.io/xk6/cmd/xk6@latest`
    - Build with xk6:
      - `xk6 build --with github.com/LeonAdato/xk6-output-statsd`.
      - This will result in a k6 binary in the current directory.
    - Run with the just built `k6:
      - $env:K6_STATSD_ENABLE_TAGS="true"
      - ./k6 run -o output-statsd {script file}

### Streaming K6 metadata to InfluxDB

- Navigate to K6Testing -> influxDb and run the following command to start InfluxDb (The name `influxdb2` can be excluded as we running the command inside the same directory as the compose file):
```
docker-compose up influxdb2
```

- To stop container run:
```
docker-compose down
```

- To run container with latest code
```
docker-compose up --build
```
- We need to create a binary that includes https://github.com/grafana/xk6-output-influxdb.
  - To build a k6 binary with this extension, first ensure you have the prerequisites:
    - [Go toolchain](https://go101.org/article/go-toolchain.html) - Download msi and install
    - [Git](https://git-scm.com/) - Download and install Git
    - [xk6](https://github.com/grafana/xk6) - Run `go install go.k6.io/xk6/cmd/xk6@latest`
    - Build with xk6:
      - `xk6 build --with github.com/grafana/xk6-output-influxdb`.
      - This will result in a k6 binary in the current directory.
    - Run with the just built `k6:
      - $env:K6_INFLUXDB_ORGANIZATION="4cd91a790e90baaf" (organization is retrieved from InfluxDB url in browser http://localhost:8086/)
      - $env:K6_INFLUXDB_BUCKET="myfirstinfluxdbbucket"
      - $env:K6_INFLUXDB_TOKEN="MyToken"
      - $env:K6_INFLUXDB_ADDR="http://localhost:8086/"
      - ./k6 run -o xk6-influxdb {script file}

### Pull data from InfluxDB into Grafana

- Run the following command to start a Grafana Docker container (Grafana could have been setup in the InfluxDb docker compose file to avoid having to use http://host.docker.internal:8086 to setup data source):
``` 
docker run -d -p 3000:3000 --name=grafana --volume "$PWD/data:/var/lib/grafana" grafana/grafana-enterprise 
```
- Setup InfluxDB as a data source. Replace the inputs appropriately as needed.

![InfluxDb data source setup in Grafana](data:image/png;base64,)

- https://grafana.com/grafana/dashboards/14801-k6-dashboard/ was used as the Dashboard Template below. The ID is 14801 if you need to import. Note that it uses InfluxQL query language.
- Navigate to K6Testing -> Grafana and import the Dashboard (K6 Dashboard with InfluxDB and Flux Query Language.json) into Grafana
